Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900) stands as a testament, its players entering from the right, traversing the horizontal as if the world itself were but a narrow strip. Even when they vanished beyond the frame's edge, the camera held its ground, unmoving.

These films were composed in long shots, the rare medium shot a whisper of intimacy never fully realized. The close-up was an unknown land, unexplored, for the tradition of theater and vaudeville left the audience at a distance, observing the whole of the stage at once. The actors remained in the middle ground, the camera a distant observer, never inviting a closer gaze.

Most trick films found their life in a singular concept, a lone shot that defined the whole. Their brevity was as a breath held, seldom more than a minute in length, each frame a flicker of vaudevillian spectacle—magic acts, vanishing illusions, transformations—bereft of narrative weight. Yet, within these films, a shot to the viewer's eye was not always as it seemed. The illusion demanded a deft hand, stitching together fragments of reality to conjure the impossible. The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) serves as a cunning example, the moment of her doomed head's severance buried within the cut, a single shot to the untrained eye, yet a patchwork of frames beneath the surface.

In the shadows of literature's past, the Gothic Novel stands as a contradiction, an "Old-New" conundrum as Ian Watt might have it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. This Gothic form has wandered through the halls of critique, derided and praised, its depths questioned, yet its 'terrible sublime' nature extolled (Burke). Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto gave birth to this genre, melding the ancient with the modern, forging a new path in the wilderness of words. Walpole drew from the old stage with its dramatic echoes and the new mimicry of nature found in the 'modern' novels to weave what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). This Gothic tale hearkens back to the medieval echoes of theatre, architecture, traditions. Even in the twilight of Otranto's release, "gothic" was a term cast upon many peoples, styles, epochs. Seen as old, unsophisticated against the bright mirror of "modern" progress, it clung to its theatrical roots even as it embraced the novel's new form, allowing the reader to peer into the souls of its characters. Thus, Gothic endured, timeless yet obsolete, new to the eyes of readers lost in the web of time.

Within these Gothic tomes, the notion of Chivalry looms large. This medieval path of the knight, both preserved and altered in the first Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry, for Gothic writers, stood as a beacon of what was once noble and brave and capable, a reflection of what they deemed absent in their world. The chivalric past, idealized, romanticized, whispers of the Gothic's future dance with Romanticism, striving to mold the present anew. Walpole, writing amidst political turmoil, despaired for the days to come. Swathed in politics and shadowed by accusations, he perhaps pondered, if not openly, the loss of inherent morality, the 'goodness' of the Gothic age, now vanished in the hearts of his contemporaries. This struggle breathes through his characters, as seen in Frederic. Before Frederic steps into the light, the reader senses his chivalric aura; a prince, wounded by life, touched by tragedy, presumed lost to the infidels. The "gallant and courteous Knight," his image swells with exaggeration, heralding the Gothic excess yet to come (66).

In the vast sprawl of commerce where the world drags its goods from one end of the earth to the other, there lies the intricate dance of supply chain management. This stream of processes, born from the mind of Keith Oliver in the year 1982, moves like a river that knows no rest, carrying the burdens of order from the moment a customer desires to the raw pulse of materials, through the labor of hands and machines, to the place where the goods find their peace in the hands of those who want them. There are six stone pillars upon which this edifice rests: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. These are the tools of those who guide the chain, the managers who bend the will of the world to offer service to those who ask it.

Production begins the tale, the first note in a symphony. It is the foundation upon which all else rests, the moment when the thoughts of what, when, where, and how take shape. It demands a keen eye on the market, the silent whisper of the people's desires, a guide in the wilderness. Here, decisions are made, the future drawn up in numbers and plans, the where and the how taking form as managers ponder the place and the machinery, the rhythm of time and the wear of tools. It is a step heavy with import, each misstep a cost of time and fortune. In the world of Wal-Mart and Target, I have seen the design, the booklet, the process that guides every hand and every step, a map in the wilderness of commerce. It is this clarity that keeps the wheels turning, the confusion at bay.

Next comes the matter of supply, the second stone in the chain. Here lie the strategic decisions, the core capabilities that define a place, the partnerships that grow like vines from decisions made. A company may split its soul, dividing the labor across many lands and hands, each with its own tools and talents. Here, the manager decides where to place the burden, which division or partner shall carry the weight. They may choose to let another carry the load, to outsource the work, and in this choice find speed, find flexibility, while holding the costs at bay.

And so the chain winds on, a path through the wilds of commerce, each step a dance, each decision a note in the song of the world.

In the grim tapestry of Victorian literature, where the minutiae of societal hierarchy often stand as the canvas, there exists a divergence in the form of Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These novels, like strange constellations in the night sky, bear the mysteries and the grotesqueries that set them apart from their contemporaries, infusing their characters with the haunted depth of dreams and enigmas. Here, motivations and emotions are laid bare as if under the light of a spectral moon.

In Oliver’s world, there is no peace. Ideas swarm his mind like spectres, and he walks not in the company of the living but with the echoes of Sikes and Crackit, their voices a discordant symphony in his ears. Even as he speaks, it is not to the world around him but to the phantoms of his consciousness. A gunshot rings out, shattering the air, and he is swept away by an unseen force, a maelstrom of sound and chaos engulfing him. Through this tumult, a gnawing pain lurks, an ever-present torment that knows no respite. (Dickens, 220)

The novels paint the landscape of mystery often with the brush of dreams or the dreamlike, each stroke differing in its intent and revelation. In Oliver Twist, these visions unveil the hidden corridors of Oliver's soul, the shadows of his anguish, and the dawning of his understanding of the world’s cruel truths. In the retelling of his shooting, Oliver is ensnared in a vivid reverie, seeking aid in a world that spins beyond his grasp. The passage underscores his impotence amidst the chaos that surrounds him, the hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit a testament to the abyss in his spirit. He is borne away, numb to the touch of the unseen hand, experiencing anew the despair born not from the sting of pain but from the fear that clings to his bones. The specter of this event raises the question of whose will guides his fate, for it is not his own. The shooting becomes a mirror to his helplessness, a reflection of his inability to seize control even as death looms. There is a whisper of defeat in this narrative, as if Fagin's shadow has begun to claim him, thrusting him deeper into a chasm of despair, shackling his will to resist. Otherwise, one might presume he would have struggled for the sake of survival, if only to grasp at life’s fleeting promise.

Time ebbs and flows, neither day nor night holding dominion. Time is a specter, gone as soon as it arrives, and night descends once more; a night that stretches endlessly in its oppressive silence, yet slips away in its brief, haunted hours.

In the dimming years past, I found myself in the hushed corridors of an after-school program, a haven for children seeking solace in books and numbers. Among them was a boy, Adrian by name, caught in a struggle with the written word. He was a small thing, perhaps in his third or fourth year of schooling, and the letters danced before him like shadows on a wall, some clear as a bell, others lost in a haze. He was Latino, that much was true, yet his English was as flawless as the summer sky.

We battled on, Adrian and I, until the day his mother came. I was minding the stragglers left behind from a field trip when she walked through the door. Her tongue was Spanish, mine barely so, but we exchanged what we could in broken phrases. It struck me then, like a sudden thunderclap, that Adrian's foe was not the words but the alphabet itself. He was a boy adrift between two worlds, and I wondered if my revelation brought him any peace. I hope, in the quiet moments, that it did.

This tale I recount to cast light on the silent barrier that is language in our schools, especially here in California. It is a barrier unseen, even to those who speak the tongue with ease. For Adrian, the cure was simple: tutoring in the letters and sounds of English. But for others, those whose voices are new to this land, the path is twisted and long. There is no single answer. The dual language system, immersion, tutors, ESL classes—none alone will mend this tear. It is in their weaving together that hope lies.

The dual language system holds promise, not just for the Spanish-speaking child, but for all. Studies whisper of its success, of children who rise above their peers. Fear hovers over this notion, fear that it is folly, a waste. But it is not so. If we embraced this as the way, rather than the exception, all children might flourish. How then do we proceed? Must every teacher wield two tongues? No, such a demand is folly. Yet, there is no reason we cannot place by their side aides, tutors, call them what you will, who speak in two voices.

From the time we are children, we are told of things vast and incomprehensible, whispers of something greater that looms just beyond the reach of our understanding. Some are led to Sunday schools, others to temples, and still others search within the confines of their own hearts for the answers. Many of us embrace the faiths handed down by those before us, while some cast them aside, denying anything beyond the orbit of their own solitary universe. We may cling to one set of beliefs only to shed them for another as we wander. Whatever path is chosen, the journey shapes us, guided by our own visions of the divine. We seek a beacon in the darkness, a light to lead us from the shadows into the day.

A cardinal, my father said when I asked him his favorite bird. We sat on the porch of our house, the rain a relentless tide upon the tin roof above, cigarettes between our fingers. The gutters spilled their burden, drowning the plants that lined the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain, a stare that seemed to reach for something unseen, part quest, part memory. He had grown thinner, his clothes draping his frame like a forgotten memory. His hair, too, had waned, sparser than I recalled. He avoided my eyes, gazing into the rain as if it might offer answers. I felt the solitude of that moment, fear clinging to me as I realized I could not speak of how much I would miss him. Words would give weight to the reality we both wished to deny. I embraced him, drew my chair nearer, and joined him in watching the rain fall in the June twilight.

My father departed this world in December, five days past my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation had not eased his pain, merely stretched his days beyond what the doctors foresaw. I pondered what value lay in such suffering. What kind of God would allow this, I wondered in the solitude of night. I uttered no prayers. If God existed, he had ceased to heed my voice long ago.

I did not wish to witness his passage from this life to another. So I did not. I could not bear to watch the life that gave me breath as it flickered out. I wanted to hold the memory of his living, not his dying. I knew him better than they did, better than his kin. I knew he would not want me as a witness to his end. So I lay curled in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

And no one even called.

In the early days of this great land, there was a man named John Taylor of Caroline, a soul deeply tethered to the soil, who spoke with fervor for the cause of Republicanism. Though his hands were calloused by the plow, his brief brush with the relentless winds of politics shaped him into a figure known for his steadfastness and his voice, ever rising in defense of the liberty of men and the governance that would allow it. His creed lay in the furrows of the earth, for it was the agrarian life he held above all, believing it to be the noblest of pursuits, and it was this belief that painted his views on the nature of sovereignty, the Constitution, and even the courts of law.

Taylor held within him a vision of a land unshackled by the chains of history. He saw a nation where the absence of ancient traditions was not a void but a canvas to inscribe a new order, a self-governance that could stand as a beacon to the world. He spoke of the inalienable rights bestowed upon all men, each linked inexorably to the other, so that to deny one was to unravel the very tapestry of freedom. Such rights, he contended, must remain beyond the reach of any government’s grasp. He understood the world as a place where, in its most primal state, those with strength and cunning would thrive at the expense of the weak, but civilization, he argued, must not mirror this savage truth.

In his mind, Taylor saw the blueprint of an ideal society, one where the government must reckon with the dual nature of man, his capacity for both light and dark. He was unyielding in his belief in a morality cleaved in two. "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human," he declared. A good government, he argued, was one that protected the sanctity of private property, nurtured the land, and held at bay the tides of unchecked capitalism. For even in a system led by those driven by greed and self-interest, a government founded on these good principles would stand just and true. Self-interest, he believed, drove all men, but it was only when this trait led to the exploitation of others that it took on the guise of evil. Thus, a vigilant government was needed to temper man's inherent wickedness and to guard against the insidious creep of corrupt principles.

Taylor, like his fellow Republicans, called for a Constitution interpreted with the utmost rigor. He envisioned a Federal government hemmed in by the strict bounds of the written word, no more powers than those clearly penned by the founders. He knew well the cost of an expansive government, the shadow of despotism it cast. Yet he warned against a reading too simple, too literal, for without the spirit of the founders to guide it, such an interpretation could be twisted to serve dark ends. To Taylor, it was the Declaration of Independence that rang truest, a document that spoke of a union of sovereign states, not a monolithic nation, and in this he placed his faith.

He stood gazing downwards, his mind a blank canvas, absorbing the view before him. With a practiced detachment he studied the scene, his thoughts moving in and out like shadows in the mind, leaving no trace. It seemed as though he had no thoughts to call his own, just a fluid experience of the sight before him.

Once, heeded the advice of an artist he knew, he bought a book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. He had wanted to draw since he was a child, and this book promised to unravel the mysteries from the pencil's touch to the brain's dance with lines. In its pages, it spoke of framing the picture, a technique to capture the chaos of detail, like a bowl of fruit amidst kitchen clutter, into a simple tableau. 

But now, as he stared at the bowl before him, he could not summon that artist's frame. Overwhelmed, he stood, filled with a sense of awe. Like Picasso's blue, Monet's greenery, or the Renaissance's rainbowed masters, if his vision had any claim to artistry, this was the genesis of his Work in Brown.

His fingers found their tool, muscles coiled and relaxed, shaping the intent of his mind into the world, crafting perhaps his life's most creative act. Water swirled, serene and clear, dissolving fragments into the void. Muscles tightened, jerked, spasmed, and his hand struck the handle again. The stubborn brown refuse clung to the porcelain, unmoving, like a slug.

With mop in hand, feet set firm, tie tight around his throat, he frowned at the insolent mass left for the hapless cleaners of Rite Aid's restrooms. A few more flushes, a few more moments of introspection, then his hand moved to the wall for the roll of paper. It wrapped around his hand, forming a makeshift oven mitt. Standing tall, then bending low, his hand descended into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

In the dim light of dawn, the roads stretch out like a silent promise, but too often they bear witness to the tragedy of youth. Young lives, untested and unready, find themselves at the wheel of death's chariot, a truth as stark as the asphalt beneath them. The National Institutes of Health speak of the adolescent mind, still forming, not yet sculpted to navigate the perils of the road. Inexperience, like a shadow, lingers in every turn and misstep, leading to the tolling bells of rolled vehicles and lives lost. 

When they gather, these young souls, in the company of their peers, the odds darken further. Common sense long departed, they ride together, unaware of the silent calculus that plays out with each mile. A study in California, that land of sun and shadow, reveals the grim correlation: the younger the passengers, the greater the likelihood of calamity.

States like California have tried to weave a tapestry of safety with provisional licenses, a patchwork of rules to limit the night wanderings and companionship on the road. Yet these are but bandages over a wound that runs deep. As a group, the youngest among us are ill-prepared for the weight of this responsibility. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman casts doubt even on the age of eighteen, suggesting the reckless thrill-seeking of youth is a fire not yet cooled.

We stand on the precipice of time, gazing into a future where the road will fill with the offspring of the Baby Boomers. By 2010, the highways will swarm with these nascent drivers, each car a potential harbinger of disaster. The legislation needed is clear, straightforward as the horizon line. Schools could still shape the minds of future drivers, but the age to take the wheel should be set no lower than eighteen. A provisional pass, a rite of passage before full freedom, would still be necessary, along with hours spent under the guiding eyes of an elder.

From the breadth of this land, a uniform law could rise, a shield for the youth who walk the thin line between life and the unknown. This is no novel suggestion, but one borne of necessity, a call to protect those who do not yet know the value of their own lives.

The paper at hand traverses the landscape of Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD, drawing a map across three distinct territories. First, an understanding of the disorder is conjured briefly upon the page. Thereafter, the means of diagnosis are laid bare, those telltale signs that signal its presence. In the end, the paper unfurls ways by which a teacher, stationed within the confines of a mainstream classroom, can lend their hand to a student shadowed by CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder, known too as Auditory Processing Disorder, speaks to the manner by which the central nervous system—those tangled webs of thought and perception—takes in the world of sound. The American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, back in the year of 2005, penned words that captured its essence: a disorder where the brain, in its silent complexity, struggles to grasp the sounds that come its way. Those afflicted hear as any other, their ears unimpeded, yet something in the brain’s labyrinthine corridors does not work as it ought—a failure to parse words from the din, to sieve conversation from the noise.

The earliest whisperings of what would come to be known as CAPD find their root in the mid-1950s, a time when the disorder bore the name of "auditory imperception." Researchers then began to pick apart the threads of communication disorders in children. An Italian cohort, Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari, embarked upon this journey in 1954, and by 1961, Kimura had introduced dichotic testing, crafting a model to fathom the workings of the auditory system that resides in our depths. A gathering of minds in 1977 kindled a fire for research on children beset by CAPD.

The disorder shows its face in myriad forms: a person may lose the sound's position in the world, struggle to discern one sound from another, fail to catch the patterns in the noise. They might not sense the shifts in speech, the undercurrents of sarcasm carried by a voice’s subtle change. A sound may be blotted out by what follows it, the sequence lost to them. They might find themselves adrift, unable to make sense of the sounds that reach them, to act upon the clues they hold. 

Diagnosis comes through the lens of systematic observation, the patient’s listening behavior and auditory function tested by those skilled in the art—be they audiologists, psychologists, or others versed in such measures. Tools and tests abound, yet none claim the throne of high success. The cause of the disorder remains elusive, a shadow without form. Tests often bombard the patient with a cacophony, asking them to pick through the noise for words, numbers, meaning. Some delve deeper, recording the echoes within the ear, measuring the responses that ripple back.

In the quiet solitude of my thoughts, I find myself drawn to the path of social work, where the suffering of children echoes like a distant thunder in my heart. The Division of Family and Children Services calls to me, a siren song to mend the broken lives of the abused and the neglected, to offer solace to families teetering on the brink. Service, respect, an ethical compass—these are the lodestars I hold dear. A commitment to bind the frayed threads between souls and to seek within myself the growth necessary to remain steadfast and true in my calling. These values, though the lifeblood of the social worker, are the very marrow of my being.

For as long as I can remember, the urge to heal others has been a constant companion, though the form it would take was shrouded in uncertainty. Through the corridors of high school and the lecture halls of college, I watched as many fled from their demons, and others sought refuge in hollow comforts. Such scenes etched themselves upon my psyche, guiding me toward a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Yet, the road ahead lay cloaked in mist. Upon graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, I paused, breathing in the summer air, wondering where it might lead me. On a languid day, a friend beckoned me to her home, where I found a boy of sixteen, eyes flickering with fear, seated uneasily on her couch. His tale unfolded—a life marred by the cruelty of those who should have been his guardians. The following day, he summoned the law to his parents' door. I drove there, determined to aid him if I could. Behind closed doors, I confided my concerns to the officers, my degree from Piedmont College lending weight to my words. They, in turn, sought my voice to speak with the boy’s parents, for the law's hands were bound. Their eyes darted nervously, weaving tales to cloak their son’s cries for help as mere manipulations, "simple" disputes they claimed. This encounter, stark in its clarity, turned my gaze firmly toward social work, to shepherd children lost amidst such "simple" familial storms.

Justice, too, stands as a pillar in the realm of social work, a beacon in the darkness. We, as a society, extol the individual, mourning those who fade into memory. Yet, this vaunted individuality often bows to the weight of ancient customs, a contradiction I cannot abide. I am a lone voice, resisting the shackles of conformity. High school and college saw my rebellion against the injustices of our world: my hair a riot of hues, my attire a canvas of my spirit, the piercings a testament to my defiance. I stood with GSBA, my voice rising against the scourge of racism and discrimination. Social justice is my creed, and I shall not waver in my stand against the injustices that mar our society's soul.

In the stillness of the night where sleep forsakes the weary, we turn to the contemplation of the models that seek to explain this restless plight known as insomnia. There are the biological models, rooted in the flesh and the blood, the genes that sing and the neurons that speak in silence. And there are the sociocultural models, the invisible hand that shapes the soul, the race, the creed, the standing in a world that turns indifferent. This paper lays bare the dissection of these models, each piece of research unearthed as one would a relic from the dust, to better understand the tale they tell. Their revelations, the clarity and the void, are weighed with the care of a judge passing sentence.

A sleep disorder is a shadow cast in many forms. It may stand alone, a primary affliction, or it may cling to the darkness of another mind's turmoil. It may arise from the body's betrayal or the poisons we take within. The Dyssomnias and the Parasomnias, these are the names we give to the specters of the night. Insomnia, Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, and their kin, they walk the line between waking and oblivion. The nightmares, the terrors, the wandering in sleep, these are the echoes of the Parasomnias. For some, the disorder is a reflection of the mind's greater unrest, a mirror to an Axis I or II affliction. This review seeks to unravel insomnia, and by its light, cast a gaze upon the broader tapestry of sleep's disquiet in the context of the biological and the sociocultural.

In the realm of the biological, the inheritance of sleep's misfortune lies in the marrow and the synapse. The neurons in the hypothalamus, bearers of orexin, hold dominion over the cycles of sleep and wake. In the silent study of mice, a truth is glimpsed: the GABAB receptors on these neurons are the gatekeepers of slumber. The GABAA receptor, when stirred to life, ushers in the quietude of sleep. But to silence it is to court anxiety's embrace and deny repose. The GABAB agonist, baclofen, extends the night’s gentle embrace (Matsuki et al., 2009). From this, we glean a whisper of understanding, that what holds true for mouse may hold true for man, that the genetic tapestry of our being weaves this tale. The absence or flaw in this receptor might cast one adrift in wakefulness, beyond the reach of medicine. The sociocultural shadow of this knowledge is that should the trait be passed down, it would alter the sleep of the inheritor, rippling through life’s pursuits, the mundane and the meaningful, a hindrance in the monotony of the everyday.

He had come to know the sprawl of University Park, a place he had wandered for nigh on two and a half years, or four and a half semesters in the reckoning of the school’s calendar. For many, and he counted himself among them, the vastness of the campus was a thing to be reckoned with. His first year, they had put him in an East Halls dormitory, out on the eastern edge of the known world if one discounted the distant stadium and the Bryce Jordan Center. From Stuart Hall, he would set out on foot toward the heart of this academic wilderness, places like Willard building, where the learned gathered. It was a trek that could stretch to twenty-five minutes if the skies darkened, as they were wont to do in State College. An alum, not long gone from these halls, had spoken of days when East Halls stood solitary, separated from the university by fields of untamed land. But time and progress had filled that void with sports fields and edifices of brick and mortar—the new Creamery, the health services building, apartments rising like stones in a field. With growth came struggle, the challenge of moving from one place to another more pronounced. What then, was the remedy for such tribulation? On this campus, it was the bicycle. But wheels alone would not suffice. Riders were needed, and the paths must be paved for their passage.

He had spoken with a friend who had taken to cycling again after years adrift. The friend, in his newfound wisdom, had wondered why he had ever ceased. “Bikes are great,” he had said. “For a while, it seemed uncool, but it’s the only way to traverse this place.” The bicycle, he knew, was the most efficient means of travel. A simple bowl of oatmeal could fuel a journey of thirty miles or more. Like many of his kind, he had taken residence off-campus, a journey from the center as far-flung as any dorm. The wisest choice he had made was to procure a bicycle. Each day, he made his way to Thomas building, a place twenty-five minutes distant by foot, but a mere five if he pressed hard upon the pedals. Yet, Pollock Road, the swiftest route to Thomas, was a path fraught with difficulty, bicycle or not. There were virtues in walking, but he found himself too burdened by the weight of time. Without his bicycle, he would have no choice but to trudge on foot. Such a walk to Thomas would steal an extra thirty to forty minutes from his day. Over a week, that was more than two and a half hours. And when he considered all the other journeys he must make, to classes, to appointments, that was time he could not afford to lose.

In the shadowed corridors of Brave New World, Aldous Huxley lays bare the specter of technology and capitalism entwined, crafting a bleak tapestry where the individual is a mere whisper lost in the roar of the collective. Here, community reigns supreme, and from the cradle, souls are molded to chase fleeting pleasures, their gaze never lifting from the shallow trough of immediate gratification. They are pawns in a grander scheme, shackled to a singular doctrine by the unseen hand of the World Controller. Through the prism of Marxist thought, one discerns Huxley's wary eye cast upon these burgeoning systems. His narrative drips with the lexicon of Marxism—homogeny, reification—each word a stone in the edifice of his critique against the economic machine rising in his era.

Capitalism stands lampooned under the Marxist banner of false consciousness, a shroud that blinds the populace to the true nature of their class tetherings, ensnaring them in self-interest. Ideological reins guide the proletariat, their strings pulled by those in power, a truth laid bare in the conditioned masses of Huxley's world. The Deltas, Gammas, and their ilk wander without true will, their minds lulled by hypnopædia into a ceaseless cycle of consumption and indulgence. The World Controller orchestrates this facade, weaving hegemony's threads to bind social classes beneath an unyielding hierarchy, where the ignorant buy into a system that chains them. Even the Alphas and Betas, except for outliers like Bernard, slumber in complicity, their awareness a dormant ember.

In this barren land, relationships fall away like dust, the characters rendered as shadows, void of depth. Perhaps Huxley whispers that the confluence of technology and capitalism erodes the spirit, stripping man of will and voice. Love is a forgotten legend; emotions are muted shades, interactions mere surface ripples. Men speak of women in terms vacuous and crass, while women recount their liaisons with a brazen air. Each class, content in its station, reflects the socioeconomic chains of capitalism, their unwavering loyalty a testament to Marxist visions of the proletariat, convinced of their supremacy as long as they tread the path of consumption, obedience, and conformity.

Thus, Huxley paints his cautionary tale, the ashes of individuality scattered by the winds of progress and profit.

Four winters past in a classroom at CBC where I first took up the study of Islam, there were voices raised in fervent debate over the nature of its creed. Was it a faith marred by the stain of hostility? I reckon now that this question holds even more weight in the present day's light. The years since the towers fell have seen the great wheel of mass media spin from suspicion and fear to a curious acceptance of Islam within these American shores. Back then, it would have seemed unthinkable for a man named Barack Obama, with his roots entwined in the Muslim world, to stand upon the threshold of the presidency.

The life of the Prophet Muhammad, as set down in the pages of his biography, caught my interest with its paradoxes. From what I had gathered, Muhammad was a man who wielded the sword to spread his faith, subjugating tribes and compelling them to embrace Islam. Yet, this biography paints him as a martyr misunderstood, a man of humility who drew followers not by force, but through the quiet power of his teachings. They came, one by one, seeking the light of what he spoke.

And in those stories, one finds echoes of another. The ministry of Jesus, whose miracles are known to the world, and the acts ascribed to Muhammad bear a strange likeness. Such as when he multiplied mutton and milk to feed forty men, a reflection of the loaves and fishes. It seems the writers would have Muhammad seen as a prophet whose life was a testament to truth and wonder, not needing to prove what was plain. But this shadowing of Jesus' own miracles seems to me an unjust imitation, a borrowing that diminishes the marvels of Christ.

The tales of conversion in Muhammad's biography stand as testaments, or so they claim. Yet, they are tales told at a distance, passed from one to another like echoes in a canyon. I found myself distrustful of these accounts, for their circuitous origins seemed to weaken rather than strengthen their claims to truth.

What sits uneasily with me is the portrayal of Muhammad as a figure of divine grace, gentle and wise beyond measure. For history, as I know it, paints a different picture, one that does not align with the gentleness ascribed to him. I wonder if those who follow him today see this history for what it is, or if they are content with the visage crafted by those who came after.

In the dim corridors of history, the voice of Jesus lingered, a whisper among the clamor of men who would shape it to their own ends. His words, once simple and clear, became tangled in the thoughts of those who followed. The path of Christianity veered away, like a river twisting from its source, until it bore scant resemblance to what it had been at its inception. Yet now, in the shadow of the world, there stirs an awareness—a slow awakening to the distance traveled from the origin. The world, in its ceaseless motion, moves towards progress. And yet there are those who cling to the past, their grip firm upon traditions handed down, unwilling to see beyond the veil of what they've known.

Among the faithful, there comes a yearning, a thirst for the truth as it was first poured. To peel away the layers of doctrine accrued over the centuries, like peeling bark from an ancient tree, to find the heartwood within. It is a journey that will not be swift. Decades, perhaps centuries, will pass before the tide turns fully. But the turning is inevitable, as sure as the sun will rise. The clock moves backward, unwinding the threads of history to reveal the tapestry as it was first woven.

In this great unraveling, there grows a movement—a return to the essence, the core of what Jesus, the man, sought to impart. As this wave sweeps across lands and seas, the church will stand steadfast, a beacon guiding those who seek. Yet as the theological clock rewinds, the myriad voices of Christendom will find harmony, the cacophony of belief yielding to a singular tune. Borders and divisions will fall away, leaving only unity in their wake. History is rich with reversals. Once, Christians were the hunted, the outcasts, scourged by the Roman Empire, only to see that empire later don the mantle of their faith. Our own nation has turned from the chains of slavery to embrace leadership from those once bound.

This coming reversion will play out upon the stage of Christendom, a grand undoing in search of the source. Diversity, once celebrated, will give way to a singular truth. And this will be made possible by reading the words of Jesus not as ironclad edicts, but as metaphors, rich with meaning and open to interpretation.

So what, then, happened since the days when Jesus walked the earth? Cast your gaze far into the past, and you find Judaism, the seed from which Christianity sprouted. Monotheism, the divine touch upon the world, and the Hebrew scriptures held sway when the Roman legions marched into Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. But even then, the Jewish people were not of one mind. Divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the multitude of common folk, each held their own vision of what should be. Yet from this crucible of belief, something new was forged.

In the heart of the city where smoke rose like a dark river against the sky, there was a place where men worked themselves into the ground, driven by the greed of those above them. The air was thick with the stench of industry, a testament to the insatiable hunger of men who would grow their empires regardless of the cost. The Jungle laid bare this truth, a tale of ambition and disregard, where the mighty chimneys spewed their filth, heedless of the lives they choked beneath their shadows.

The factory owners, their eyes fixed on profit, cared little for the souls toiling in the bellies of their machines. Sinclair's words cut through the smoke, revealing a world where human worth was measured against a dollar and found wanting. There was no room for loyalty, no place where decency might find a foothold. In this seething pit of jealousy and hatred, men were cast aside without thought, their labor spent and their lives discarded as easily as the refuse that lined the streets of Packingtown.

In those days, the law was silent, and the workers bore their burdens alone. The managers, unchecked, drove them harder, faster, into the maw of progress. The conditions were brutal, relentless, and the people who endured them were little more than slaves to a system that offered no escape. Even the unions, those supposed bastions of hope, turned against them, profiting from their plight.

Sinclair painted a world where survival teetered on the edge of starvation, where morality was as scarce as the warmth of the sun through the smoke. The men who held the reins were as ruthless as any slave driver, and under their rule, the city was a place of despair. In the eyes of the workers, there was no end, no respite, only the endless grind of a world that turned without care or compassion. And so they labored, caught in the web of their own making, bound to the whims of those who held their fate in callous hands.

In the shadowlands of Edgar Allan Poe’s mind, there lay a poem he deemed among his finest—“Dream-Land.” Within its verses, the word “Thulé” emerges, twice invoked as if to bind the spectral narrative at its edges. Mabbott traces this term’s lineage back to Virgil, who spoke of Thulé as an island adrift at the world's edge, north of Britain, where the known world frayed into myth. Yet Virgil’s voice is not the only echo in Poe’s work. The Germanic allure, the whispering of Goethe’s pen, held sway over him.

This tether to Goethe is no mere shadow. Karl J. Arndt, in his musings on Poe's "Politian" and Goethe's "Mignon," threads a connection between their verses, positing that Poe wandered in the paths Goethe once trod. The Oxford Companion to English Literature speaks of Goethe, celebrant of the poetic drama “Faust,” which unfurled in two acts, the first in 1808, the last in the breath of Goethe’s own departure in 1832. Within Faust’s latter part, a poem named “The King of Thulé” resides—a tale of a king, whose queen’s parting gift, a goblet, became his anchor to memory and sorrow. He drank deeply from it, and when the weight of life pressed too heavily, he cast the goblet to the sea and followed it into the abyss.

The king’s lament, his isolation, and his descent into shadow echo the landscape of Poe’s “Dream-Land,” where the speaker wanders amid the ghosts of friends and a world devoid of hue. It is as if Poe stood at the edge of Goethe’s creation, a dark reflection of his own losses and the solace he found in drink. The resonance of Thulé also reached “The Pit and the Pendulum” less than a year before, marking Poe’s fascination with the term.

Poe’s invocation of Thulé straddles his oeuvre, a spectral thread linking “The Pit and the Pendulum” and “Dream-Land.” The two pieces breathe as companions, “The King of Thule” and “Dream-Land” entwined. Thulé, in Poe’s vision, is a realm of desolation, haunted, a vista of shadows much like the mournful king’s domain in Goethe’s dirge. Poe steps into Goethe’s lament, his own sorrows mirrored in the king’s fatal gesture.

In Goethe, Poe found a kinship, drawn not only by the pull of Tennyson’s name but by the very tide of reproductions that carried Goethe’s work across time and place, into Poe’s own hands. The German poet’s influence seeped into the fibers of Poe’s being, a spectral dialogue across the ages.

In the state of California, the question arises whether a patron, finding herself sprawled upon the floor of a grocery store, having slipped upon an ungainly puddle of applesauce left untended, might claim punitive damages with the assertion that the store's overseer acted with malice. The tale unfolds thus: though twice informed of the treacherous mess, the manager, with indifference borne of hunger, delayed its removal for the sake of his supper.

The court, in its deliberation, would be hesitant to cast aside Jennifer Palmer’s plea for punitive recompense without due consideration. For the law demands evidence of a reckless and conscious disregard for the inevitable harm that such negligence might bring, conduct that courts must find despicable in its essence. Palmer, in her lament, shall argue that the manager, one Martin by name, ought to have foreseen the peril of leaving the spill uncleansed, for the annals of the store bore witness to numerous such misfortunes in the months preceding her own calamity. Yet, with such foreknowledge, Martin remained inert.

The charge of despicable conduct may seem less robust, yet Palmer’s case holds ground, given the history of six prior slip-and-fall mishaps within that fateful year of 2009, all under Martin’s watchful eye, and still, no measures did he take to secure the safety of his patrons.

On a day marked by the unlucky digits of October 13, in the year two thousand and nine, as the clock struck five in the evening, a missive was delivered by Rich Wayne, a loyal employee of D&D Markets, to his superior, Paul Martin. The message was clear: an applesauce spill sullied an aisle. But Martin, ensconced in his meal, dismissed it with a wave, claiming no time for such trifles. A quarter of an hour passed, and another messenger, Mary J. Haddigan, brought the same warning. Yet Martin, steadfast in his neglect, offered the same reply. At the half-hour's mark, Jennifer Palmer, unsuspecting, found her footing lost, and with it, her well-being, as she met the unforgiving ground, her back injured.

The annals of that year recorded five prior slip-and-fall encounters at the establishment known as D&D. Now, Palmer seeks reparations both compensatory and punitive for her trials, and the question put forth is whether to seek a partial dismissal of her claim for punitive damages.

Under the statutes of California, a grievance unmoored from contractual bounds may yield punitive damages if it is shown that the wrongdoer acted with oppression, fraud, or malice as defined by law. Malice, in this context, would be an act intended to cause harm, or if not by intent, then by despicable conduct carried out with willful and conscious disregard for the safety of others. The courts have seen fit to label as malicious those acts undertaken with such disregard, where the defendant was aware of the likely harm their actions might cause, yet chose, with deliberation, to ignore the perilous outcomes. Such is the precedent set in the case of Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co.

Thus, the tale is set before the court, the outcome yet to be written in the annals of justice.

She'd always felt it, that yearning, a need that would not be sated, a hunger that gnawed at the edges of her young soul. It began when she was fourteen, just stepping into the unruly world of adolescence. And now, three years on at seventeen, it lingered still, a shadow cast over her days. She'd come to reckon it was someone she sought, not something, and yet no boy had stirred her heart. They'd come, awkward and earnest, those boys, with their clumsy overtures, but none could breach the fortress of her indifference. She'd pondered this anomaly, puzzled over this disquiet that set her apart from other girls her age, but no answer came. Just theories, frail and unsatisfying, and so she moved through her life, questioning her desires in silence.

Home was a sanctuary, a place of peace. Her parents were good folk, calm and even-tempered, their disagreements rare and fleeting like the last rays of sunlight. Their quarrels with her were rarer still, mostly confined to her own assertions of independence, her spirited rebellion against their gentle rule. She was their daughter, their bright and lively counterpoint, her vivacity a beacon that drew others to her, an easy charm that endeared her to many.

But today peace was a stranger. She wandered from room to room, seeking some new spark for her restless mind, when a cry pierced the air, sharp and sudden, her mother's voice like a bell tolling in the quiet. Panic rose in her, a swift tide, and she flew to the kitchen, calling out, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mother lay there, crumpled on the floor, pain etched across her face as she gasped out "Ow" with each shallow breath. The girl knelt beside her, her hand gentle on her mother's arm, her voice steady. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words came in a rush, strained and urgent, and the daughter could see the depths of her mother's suffering. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." With her mother's guidance, she gathered her strength, grateful for the lessons that had taught her how to bear such a burden. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back seat, and drove with purpose.

The hospital was a place of antiseptic smells and whispered fears, but these she did not notice, her mind fixed on her mother, her heart a drum in her chest. She bore the injured woman inside, her voice rising above the sterile clamor, summoning aid. Faces turned, concern etched in their lines, and a bed was brought, her mother lifted onto it, whisked away to where she could be cared for. And there the daughter sat, alone with her worry, the minutes stretching into hours.

Her mother had fallen, toppled from a stool in her quest for a vase that rested beyond her reach, high up in the kitchen's tallest cupboard.

In the quiet corridors of study and the echo of diligent footsteps, a journey took place, a search for truth amid the patterns of life and the whispers of mortality. The Mediterranean Diet, a whisper of ancient customs and sun-drenched lands, was laid bare in its essence. A score, an alternate Mediterranean score they called it, a quantification of the diet's embrace, a beacon against the shadow of chronic heart disease and the silent thief of stroke.

This score, this marker, was a reflection of the earth's bounty, of plant foods and the humble legume, of nuts and grains and the silent revolution of monounsaturated fats. The creatures of the sea, they too played their part, and the vine's fruit allowed its modest indulgence. Gone were the heavier fare of flesh and the burden of saturated fat.

In the annals of study past, there was murmurings of this diet's power, of lives extended and hearts spared. Yet, the specter of stroke, of its sudden silence, had remained unexamined, a shadow in the corner of their knowing.

And so they followed them, these women of healing hands and watchful eyes, through the seasons of life, from the vigor of youth to the autumn of their years. Seventy-four thousand eight hundred eighty-six souls, bound by their calling, their lives a tapestry of data and insight. They spoke of their meals, of their choices, in the language of questionnaires, their words distilled into a score that spoke of adherence.

Year after year, the numbers were gathered, scrutinized, validated against the truth of hospital records and the finality of death's certificate. Stories of heart's failure and the silent stroke were corroborated, some left in the realm of the probable, yet included in the tale. Their habits, their weights, the air they drew into their lungs, all these were woven into the narrative.

The numbers were more than mere numbers; they were the tale told by the data, a story of risk and adherence. A model was built, a construct of hazard and probability, a tool to divine the future from the past.

And in the end, the pattern was revealed. Those who walked closest to the Mediterranean way, those whose scores were high, found themselves less touched by the specter of heart's malady and the silent stroke. Over the span of two decades, the numbers spoke. Two thousand three hundred ninety-one hearts failed, one thousand seven hundred sixty-three strokes struck, and all toll, one thousand seventy-seven souls were claimed by cardiovascular fate. Yet those who embraced the diet, who stood in the highest quintile, knew a lesser risk, a relative risk of 0.71, a testament to the power of what they chose to consume.

In this study lay a truth, quiet and persistent, a whisper of hope carried on the winds of knowledge and the promise of a path less traveled.

In the streets of a city far from home stands a figure solitary and defiant. The sign she holds bears a message scrawled in black, stark and unsettling, for it speaks of evil still breathing in the world. Burma, they call it, a land under the shadow of tyranny, where power was seized and held with an iron fist since the year of 1962. The monks in their robes of saffron rose against it, their protests a cry for justice that echoed in the streets and beyond. Yet the world turned, and the military with it, into a force of ruin and rage. Monasteries fell to their wrath, and the streets ran with fear and blood. The tales of those days tell of a Japanese man, Kenji Nagai, whose life was taken on a September day in 2007, in a moment that marked the cost of truth. The numbers they speak of are but shadows of the truth, for those who fled speak of thousands lost to the silence of graves unmarked and unseen.

Such is the way of the world, where power seeks to silence all that defies it. In the histories of man are the echoes of empires long fallen, where rulers claimed divine right over the souls of men. In lands far east, the rulers wore the guise of gods themselves, leading their people with promises woven through steel and tradition. In the land of the free, they say, a man of power confers with the voices of the blind, guiding his hand in the affairs of the many.

The stories of resistance are many, and they are written in the blood of those who stood against the tide. In a square named Tiananmen, they gathered, the youth and the brave, to speak against the chains of rule, and the numbers of their loss are whispered in corridors of power as the truth lies buried beneath the weight of silence. Across the world, in Rwanda, the land was stained with the blood of its own, as neighbor turned upon neighbor, and the earth drank deep from the well of human hatred. Farther still, in the lands darkened by the shadow of a Reich, the cries of the innocent were silenced in the fires of madness, as the world watched and wept.

These are the tales of our time, the stories that shape the days upon which we walk, and they are written in the names of those who stood and those who fell.

In the annals of jazz, where the echoes of brass and reed hold sway over the shadows of time, Duke Ellington's legacy looms large and enduring. His life stretched long over the keys of the piano and the stands of the orchestra, and his creative spirit shaped the music that rose like smoke from the fires he kindled in the hearts of his players. Ellington's hands on the piano were like whispers, subtle in their presence, yet as a composer, he sculpted pieces of such depth and complexity that they became monuments to the talents of his band. He laid down the paths over which soloists could wander free, and he wrote with precision, calling forth the voices of his musicians to give breath to the music's ideas. In this, he found the tone of the orchestra, a voice unified and original, each piece a testament to his mastery of sound and the interplay of parts within the whole. In the history of jazz, his works stand among the most innovative and brilliant, like constellations in a vast, dark sky.

The Grove Music dictionary, a tome of knowledge on the sounds of Ellington, speaks of Creole Love Call, where he took the human voice and made it an instrument of jazz, a thread in the tapestry of sound. It was here, early in his journey, he wove voice into the fabric of music, adding texture and hue unburdened by words. This piece, Creole Love Call, stands as a testament to his gift for complementing the style of his soloists, a gift that would shine through the years. The slow, deliberate blues, twelve bars long, unfolds in six choruses:

Chorus 1: A dance of call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins soft and smooth, then grows rougher as it fades.

Chorus 2: The muted trumpet takes its turn, expanding the melody and lingering on the blue notes, like shadows stretching in the dusk.

Chorus 3: A clarinet rises, high and sweeping, with a piano whispering beneath in syncopated rhythm.

Chorus 4: The full band takes up the call, echoing the first chorus, brass and reeds speaking in turn.

Chorus 5: The peak of the piece, as reeds now lead the call, high and clear, with the brass and rhythm sections marking time in syncopated stops.

Chorus 6: A return to the beginning, the voice and reeds in call and response, the voice now growling, a beast of sound.

Tag: A brief closure, a vocal run and a trombone’s dissonant finale.

Ellington’s use of voice as a brush to paint the music's colors is a trait that marks his work throughout.

In the year that followed, with Hot and Bothered, Ellington wove tight orchestration with his ear for the colors of sound. A call and response between “Bubber” Miley’s muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing, where the trumpet spoke in vocal tones and the voice sang with the spirit of instruments, blending into a rich tapestry. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) pushed these ideas further, as Ellington called upon Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a stalwart of his orchestra, to introduce the melody on his muted trombone, a sound that carried the weight of the world.

In the quiet halls of time, where nature's hand shapes the world unseen, the question lingers like smoke on the horizon: why do creatures change their form as they do? What binds or frees them on this path of transformation? D'Arcy Thompson in the year of our Lord 1917 spoke of the zoologist's dream, a dream yet unfulfilled, the hope to capture life's simplest forms in the cold precision of mathematics. And though years have passed, much remains the same. The minds of men have turned to numbers and models, tracing the lineage of mollusks and their shells, those ancient homes and armors, through the ages of their becoming.

In our study, we reach out into the dark, seeking the patterns of change in Prunum, that humble dweller of the sea, melding the abstract with the experimental. We use the light that pierces bone and shell alike, the X-ray's eye, to carve out the secrets held within. In these images, we find the whispers of form, the hard lines of geometry in nature's hand. We take these lines and feed them into CerioShell, a device of stone and code, to conjure shapes that might have been, could be, or never were. We seek the borders of what can be, and what cannot, in the world of shells.

Consider the shell, a spiral path through the void, a helix cast in calcium and time. Each turn, each whorl, winds about an unseen axis, the columella, the spine of this small universe. The whorls grow as they will, each with its own pace, separated by the fine line of the suture. The last is the greatest, the body whorl, and the spire rises above it, all its kin save the last. At the peak, the apex, and at the other end, the base. The creature within reaches out through the aperture, a portal to the world beyond.

To see the shell, one must turn it in the mind's eye, view it from above, below, and every angle it permits. The apertural gaze is the common one, the opening toward you, the peak above. Whorls are counted from the first suture, the shell split by a line, and the count moves in fractions, a quarter of a whorl here and there.

A shell, a journey through time, marked by the apertures' path, a record of the life it shields. One can map this path, plot the coordinates of each whorl's opening, the radius that defines its reach. And with this map, this formula of life, one can alter the course, reshape the growth that nature ordained.

In this, we seek understanding, a glimpse into the hidden workings of the world, the dance of numbers and life entwined.

In the shadowed archipelago of Indonesia, time has etched its slow passage upon the land, the cries of newborns and the silence that follows marking a decade's tale unchanged. The country strides toward some of its appointed destinies, the water and the cleansing of the land, yet the health of the young and those who bear them lags in its wake, a tale of unmet hopes and goals left to drift as they approach the year of reckoning, 2015. Such is the state of things as they stand, the reasons manifold, pointing to the need for a stronger foundation in the healing arts rather than the mere patchwork of programs.

The land has seen the hands of skilled healers at the birth of its children, a number reaching seventy-two parts of a hundred. Yet among these ranks walk traditional hands, midwives whose knowledge is deep yet cannot stem the tide when the blood flows too freely. Thus, the shadows of mothers lost to the hemorrhage remain unchanged, a testament to the work still to come. The healing of the young is likewise in decline, as fewer cases of the sickness of the gut in the young see the hands of healers. The records of care after the cries have quieted are sparse, yet the signs speak of concern, a low echo across the land.

In the realm of birthing by the knife, the numbers fall short of what they ought to be, a mere four in a hundred. This speaks of another shadow, the disparity between the city and the fields. In the crowded cities, the knife sees the light seven times out of a hundred, but in the rural quiet, only twice. The gulf of care stretches wide across the land, with the cities gathering the healers to their heart, leaving the fields to their own devices. And there is another divide, a chasm of wealth. The poorest and the richest stand twenty-seven steps apart in their seeking of care. The poor, burdened by the cost, find the way to healing barred.

As the land contemplates its course, the question looms, vast and echoing. How best to mend the wounds of service unmet? Should the land weave a tapestry of programs, each with its own thread, or should it forge a stronger whole, looking beyond the first cries and the silence that follows? The allure of programs is clear, with their narrow focus and swift returns. Yet there are shadows here as well. To favor one area is to starve another, the workers drawn like moths to the flame of resources. The tale of funds for one cause and the lack for another is an old one, told in the echoes of the past. And when many programs run their own course, the threads tangle, each unknowing of the other, and the weight of forms and papers grows heavy.

Thus the land stands at the crossroads, the path ahead shrouded in mist, waiting for the light to break the dawn.

In the span of a century, the landscape of Popular Music has unfurled like an endless tapestry, its threads weaving into countless genres, each distinct yet interwoven. To speak their names is to attempt to capture the wind. Rap, rock, country, jazz, folk—each a tree in a vast and tangled forest, bearing branches of sub-genres and sub-sub-genres that reach out to touch the very edges of musical imagination. Among these, the heavy metal rock stands as a formidable giant, both expressive and diverse, casting its shadow over the last four decades. It is a language of emotion, one that speaks in tones often shrouded in shadow. Its diversity lies in the freedom it grants, for soon after its birth, it shed its skin to reveal a multitude of faces, each a sub-genre, each a testament to its pliability, and so the lineage continues, branching and re-branching into the present day.

We find ourselves now at a crossroads in the heavy metal saga, a place where the paths are so many and so varied that to define heavy metal is to grasp at smoke. It has become a vessel for themes borrowed from other realms, yet its roots run deep in time and memory. To comprehend the metal music that thrums through the world today, one must first seek to understand the metal movement, a force unto itself, more than mere genre.

Metal is a movement carved from the essence of darkness. It is a symphony of the extreme—more bass, more volume, more violence, more spectacle. It eschews the primitive for the virtuosic; those who wield its power do so with skill honed and sharp. It is, as one might expect, a movement steeped in the haze of drugs. The psychedelic tide of the mid-seventies swept many into realms untold, birthing records that seemed to echo from other worlds, the drugs a muse and a scapegoat both. It is a music that embraces the dark and the visceral, a stark contrast to the sunlit melodies that had long reigned. In its later incarnations, metal draws from the Romantic's dark well, its influence etched in lyrics that whisper of shadows and the void.

Consider the words of Helter Skelter, a song born of the Beatles' dalliance with their own darkness. It rides the tumultuous wave of highs and lows, perhaps the echo of substances unnamed. Regarded by some as a harbinger of heavy metal, it was the Beatles' retort to the Rolling Stones' own descent into the heavier, darker side of sound. Thus, it found its place upon The White Album, a testament to a band's unyielding desire to prove their mettle against their peers.

In the years before the Surrealists would cast their visions upon canvas, there was Henri Rousseau, a man crafting dreams both in pigment and in his own heart. The Dream, wrought by his hand in 1910, is not merely the depiction of a woman, eyes wide with wonder at a fantastical realm within her slumber. It stands also as a mirror to Rousseau’s own aspirations. A painter yearning for the nod of approval, the embrace of kindred spirits, and the applause of those who reveled in art. Yet, he found himself torn, a man beset by a quandary as old as the stars. To walk the path laid by others, to echo their strokes and gain their acceptance, or to stride alone, unshackled, and carve his own trail in the wilderness of creation. The Dream, in its essence, is this struggle incarnate. 

To understand this painting, one must first know the man behind it. Born on the twenty-first of May, 1844, in Laval, France, Rousseau was the son of a tinsmith, a merchant who tasted the sweet fruits of bourgeois life. No academies molded his hand; he labored instead as a humble gabelou, collecting tolls for the state until he reached his fortieth year. They called him douanier, though wrongly, for never was he a customs inspector. Life dealt him blows, harsh and unrelenting. His first wife, Clémence, passed from this world, leaving him a single daughter, Julia, amidst the sorrow of eight lost infants. In the wake of grief, Rousseau turned to the canvas, seeking solace and rebirth. Unlike his contemporaries who draped the peasant in romantic hues, Rousseau painted from the heart of the folk, with dreams and desires as common as any man’s.

It is no wonder, then, that Rousseau’s longing for acceptance by the art world burned so fiercely within him. Untrained, he entered the fray of art late, surrounded by the luminaries of his time. His recognition came only as Matisse began to etch his name among the stars. In the telling of Jan Gordon, within the tome of Modern French Painters, Matisse and Rousseau stood as rivals not just in paint but in purpose. Where Matisse recoiled from the trite, Rousseau yearned to be conventional, to find his place among the esteemed halls of the Artiste Français.

In the quiet of contemplation, many a thinker has mused upon the tether that binds ethics to aesthetics, truth to beauty. I reckon there's a deep reason for this kinship, as Keats whispered in his “Ode on a Grecian Urn,” where he saw beauty and truth as kindred spirits, inseparable and sufficient unto themselves. Much of what we gather in our journey is gleaned through learning or the hard edge of experience. Yet, as Keats suggests, we find within us an understanding of ethics and aesthetics, unbidden and untaught. They are more of a revealing than a dictating. In our search for the moral and the beautiful, we strive not to set rules but to grasp the why of it all—the why of a painting's allure or an action's righteousness.

But here lies the crux, the elusive heart of it. No critique of art nor discourse on morals can ever seize fully what is good or what is beautiful. When you stand before the mystery of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, all talk of foreground and contrast falls away, leaving only the ineffable truth that it is art, that it is good. When asked of one's favored work, often comes the mumble of “There's just something about it,” a prelude to the more tangled explication. I hold that art and morals cannot be entirely pinned down by their traits. As O'Connor put it, a tale says what no statement can. However minutely we dissect the layers of a story, a transcendence remains, just beyond reach. Ethics, too, bears this ethereal quality. Wittgenstein spoke of ethics as unutterable, as transcendental. It is perhaps this very “something,” this elusive essence, that is the soul of art and morality, their most potent bond.

I believe that art and ethics are thus entwined because they strike us deeply, at a level beyond words, a noumenal realm if you will, borrowing from Kant. They move us in ways felt but not fully spoken. This bond is strongest in literature, where the moral line is drawn clearer than in other arts, like music. Literature, with its stories steeped in life's own values, speaks to us because of the truths we uncover there, truths as entwined with life as they are with the written word.

The Germany of today stands as a formidable entity, a land bound by its own culture that stretches from the shadowed foothills of the Alps in München to the distant Baltic shores of Kiel. This culture flows like a river from Köln upon the Rhine, coursing through the heart of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. In such a tapestry of history and tradition, it is no wonder that Germany's roots are a mingling of tribes and distant origins.

In the mists of antiquity lies Germania, cradle of the German people. The etymology of its name remains a mystery, a puzzle for scholars and historians. Tacitus spoke of a tribe called the Tungrians, known in times past as Germans, who crossed the Rhine to clash with the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar, in his chronicles of the Gallic Wars, coined "Germanus" to describe tribes beyond his conquest, those who lay across the Rhine with intentions vague and oft mischievous. The Gauls themselves whispered this name, a mark to distinguish the conquered from the free. The origin eludes certainty; some say it harks to the Gaulish tongue, a neighbor's call. In the earliest pages of his tales, Caesar writes, "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war... They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles" (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC). Others muse it may come from the spear, the "ger," or from the Old Irish "garim," to shout, for the Germans were loud and boisterous folk (Names of Germany).

In Tacitus' ancient hand, the tale of the Germans was penned in AD 98, a testament to their origin. He wrote, "I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive... Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?" (Tacitus, 98).

And who among the Romans would forsake Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans themselves, not in those early days. They sent their legions into the lands of Germania, seeking goods and the occasional conquest, yet they returned to their vast empire. As the Germanic tribes emerged in the mid-first century, they lingered at the Empire's edge, trading their harvests and their martial prowess, serving even within the Roman ranks (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17).

In the murk of Twelfth Night's tangled web, disguise serves as a tool, a mask to cloak the soul in layers of deceit, yet there lies a perilous edge. For in the shedding of that mask, one risks a solitude deeper than any night's dark. The choice stands stark: to preserve oneself or to salvage the fragile bonds with others. Deception's revelation can stir the hearts to neutrality or ignite a fire of affront, leaving the trickster stranded in a barren land of their own making.

Turn then to the masquerade of gender, a riddle within a riddle. Why does one forsake their own skin for another's guise? Viola's plight is survival cloaked in necessity: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town / Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help / I was preserved to serve this noble count..." cast adrift in foreign lands, her womanhood a vulnerability to be hidden under the mantle of manhood. Yet, this artifice carves a chasm between her and the women who might be her allies, leaving her adrift. And in her deception, Olivia's eyes mistake her for Sebastian, a love misaligned: "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." Compounded by the clandestine yearnings between her and Orsino, "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times / Thou never shouldst love woman like to me."

In modern eyes, perhaps Twelfth Night unveils more than it conceals, the artifice prying open hearts to hidden truths. Olivia and Orsino, caught in the play of shadows, grapple with desires unspoken. Is Olivia's heart drawn to Cesario for the semblance of a man, or does it whisper a deeper truth? Yet, in this dance, Shakespeare's Olivia more likely mirrors the folly of those who love with eyes alone. Her heart turns from Cesario to Sebastian with ease, a fleeting infatuation replaced by kinship: "A sister, you are she."

Thus, the play stands as a testament to the folly and the fear in the artifice of man, a mirror held to nature's own face, reflecting the shadows and the light that dwell within.

In the chronicles of men and their deeds, the German colonial empire stands as a testament to varied endeavors and the shadow of its own making. In the land called German South West Africa, the echoes of brutality linger, a reaper's song carried upon the wind. The Ovaherero and Nama bore witness to the cruel hand of empire, a hand that knew no mercy. Yet to see the empire as a monolith would be to blind oneself to its complexities, for its reach was as diverse as the lands it claimed.

When the British set foot upon the soil of German East Africa, they found not savagery but a people versed in the written word, the fruits of German educational efforts laid bare before them. In places like Kamerun, praise was sung of the schools and the learning they nurtured. But in the harsh expanse of South West Africa, a different story was penned. Here the burden of educating the native fell not to the state but to the missionaries, and the support they received was meager, a shadow of what was given to the education of Europeans in that barren land.

In South West Africa, the schools that stood were for the Europeans, the state schools and the missionary schools alike, guided by a hand more generous than what the natives ever knew. And so it was that the majority of the native folk remained untouched by the light of learning, their minds left fallow and their tongues unlettered. The reasons for this divergence lay deep in the soil of the land, rooted in the social and political winds that blew across it. This telling seeks to dig deep and uncover those roots, to understand the minds of the settlers and the colonial masters who held sway over the lives of the people.

The writings on German colonial rule are many, penned in the tongue of that faraway land, penned in a time when the empire still stood. These early accounts sought only to describe the schools, the methods, the means. Later studies, crafted in English, took up the mantle, drawing lines between the colonies, comparing, contrasting, seeking to understand. Among the most prominent of these is Cohen's work, a study of South West and East Africa, a tale of two colonies and the paths they trod. Cohen speaks of settlers and their influence, of how the white man's presence shaped the schools and the lives of those around them.

South West Africa, a land of deserts and dry winds, yet with a climate that did not wholly drive the settlers away. By 1913, fifteen thousand white souls called it home, a number far greater than the next largest settler colony, East Africa, where just over five thousand made their lives. These numbers, these people, are part of the story, a story of education, of empire, and of those who lived in its shadow.

In the annals of history, the United States and Mexico stand as testament to a rivalry that, like a slow-burning fire, smoldered through the years, igniting here and there from 1836 to 1893. The zenith of this conflict found its form in the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States cast its shadow upon Mexico, wresting from it Texas and the American Southwest, claiming them as new dominions. The tumult between these nations was not a thing of singularity, but rather a continuum of skirmishes that gradually withered before the dawn of the First World War. The genesis of this discord lay in the clashing souls of Americans and Mexicans, divided by the chasms of religion, culture, and the stark clash of their material desires.

In this, they were not unlike others, for nations clasped by borders often find themselves at odds, their interests rubbing raw against one another, spurring rivalries that span lifetimes. The United States and Mexico, their border a line of contention, mirrored the myriad rivalries of nations whose lands adjoin. As David M. Pletcher noted, only in Mexico and Cuba did the United States grapple with enduring diplomatic quandaries, while other Latin American nations wove more harmonious ties.

Religion, that ancient wellspring of division, carved a rift between the United States and Mexico, echoing the struggles of countless nations before them. Sally Frahm observed that if the Americans of the twentieth century stood against fascism and communism, their forebears of the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries waged their silent war against Catholicism and monarchy. This ideological struggle, akin to the Cold War's dance of shadows with the Soviet Union, was rooted not in governance but in the sacred preferences of these two peoples. The distrust was a legacy, passed down from the bygone days of English and Spanish enmity, a phantom that haunted the path to cordial relations between these two nations.

In their reckoning, Diehl and Goerts chronicled seventeen disputes that marked the 57-year saga, most of which were territorial squabbles, frontier quarrels that flared with border raids by bandits and outlaws. These incursions troubled the peace of American border towns, a scourge that lingered until both nations wielded their military might to bring order to their shared boundaries.

As the years unfurled, the rivalry's fervor began to wane. Schmitt elucidates that Mexico found itself tethered to the United States in a substantial manner, the tether being a shift in American ambition from mere territorial conquest to the economic overtures of the late 19th century, drawing the curtain on a rivalry that had shaped the fates of nations.

Fifteen winters past, I found myself undone by an ailment that crept upon me unseen, unbidden, a shadow in the night. I was a nurse then, bound to the path not of dreams but of necessity, the certainties of work tethered to the frailty of flesh. "You'll always find a place," they said. "In sickness, there's always need." So it was I turned from the callings of the pen and the mysteries of the world to the care of the ailing, though my heart longed for other shores.

I stood at the crossroads, forty-six years worn, unanchored, the coffers bare of treasure, and my hands empty of toil. My body, once a vessel of strength, now betrayed me. For fifteen years, I've clung to the lifeline of Social Security, living in the shadowlands of what once was, with naught to claim as mine. The struggle's an ever-present specter, an assault upon the fortress of self. Yet amidst the wreckage, one truth stands unyielding. Were it not for kin and the few steadfast souls who call me friend, I would have long since been adrift, strength sapped by the storm that is calamity.

The lesson is this: life is an unpredictable tempest, with storms both mighty and mundane. No fortress is impregnable, no preparation absolute. Some trials demand more than solitary endurance.

In this land of ours, there's talk of forsaking the decay of government largesse for the self's refuge. But I hold instead to the hope of rekindling trust among neighbors, of hands extended in aid rather than each soul retreating to their own solitary bastion.

The tale told by those who speak of rugged individualism is one of myth. Our forebears were not sustained by isolation but by the ties that bind, the compassion that bridges, the sharing of meager means.
