Pletcher noted, only in Mexico and Cuba did the United States grapple with enduring diplomatic quandaries, while other Latin American nations wove more harmonious ties.

Religion, that ancient wellspring of division, carved a rift between the United States and Mexico, echoing the struggles of countless nations before them. Sally Frahm observed that if the Americans of the twentieth century stood against fascism and communism, their forebears of the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries waged their silent war against Catholicism and monarchy. This ideological struggle, akin to the Cold War's dance of shadows with the Soviet Union, was rooted not in governance but in the sacred preferences of these two peoples. The distrust was a legacy, passed down from the bygone days of English and Spanish enmity, a phantom that haunted the path to cordial relations between these two nations.

In their reckoning, Diehl and Goerts chronicled seventeen disputes that marked the 57-year saga, most of which were territorial squabbles, frontier quarrels that flared with border raids by bandits and outlaws. These incursions troubled the peace of American border towns, a scourge that lingered until both nations wielded their military might to bring order to their shared boundaries.

As the years unfurled, the rivalry's fervor began to wane. Schmitt elucidates that Mexico found itself tethered to the United States in a substantial manner, the tether being a shift in American ambition from mere territorial conquest to the economic overtures of the late 19th century, drawing the curtain on a rivalry that had shaped the fates of nations.

Fifteen winters past, I found myself undone by an ailment that crept upon me unseen, unbidden, a shadow in the night. I was a nurse then, bound to the path not of dreams but of necessity, the certainties of work tethered to the frailty of flesh. "You'll always find a place," they said. "In sickness, there's always need." So it was I turned from the callings of the pen and the mysteries of the world to the care of the ailing, though my heart longed for other shores.

I stood at the crossroads, forty-six years worn, unanchored, the coffers bare of treasure, and my hands empty of toil. My body, once a vessel of strength, now betrayed me. For fifteen years, I've clung to the lifeline of Social Security, living in the shadowlands of what once was, with naught to claim as mine. The struggle's an ever-present specter, an assault upon the fortress of self. Yet amidst the wreckage, one truth stands unyielding. Were it not for kin and the few steadfast souls who call me friend, I would have long since been adrift, strength sapped by the storm that is calamity.

The lesson is this: life is an unpredictable tempest, with storms both mighty and mundane. No fortress is impregnable, no preparation absolute. Some trials demand more than solitary endurance.

In this land of ours, there's talk of forsaking the decay of government largesse for the self's refuge. But I hold instead to the hope of rekindling trust among neighbors, of hands extended in aid rather than each soul retreating to their own solitary bastion.

The tale told by those who speak of rugged individualism is one of myth. Our forebears were not sustained by isolation but by the ties that bind, the compassion that bridges, the sharing of meager means. Those pioneers who carved paths through the Rockies did not do so on the strength of one alone.

So let preparedness be your ally. I have gathered my own provisions, the tools against disaster, the candles and the cans, the means to purify and shield. A plot of land to yield the earth's bounty is wisdom, as is the warmth of a wood stove in places where walls grant no solace.

Yet in preparing, look beyond the stockpile. Know the faces that dwell near, the names that echo through the hollow halls of your neighborhood. For in the end, it is the ties we forge that will light the way through the darkness.

In the misted annals of time, perhaps in that shadowed stretch of years we name the fifth or sixth century before the common reckoning, there was born a prince. This child, in the years of his wandering and enlightenment, would be known to the world as the Buddha. He cast aside the trappings of the world, found a path through the fog of human suffering, and his words laid the stone for what would become Buddhism. And of this vast edifice, Theravada stands as the most ancient pillar. The faith, now aged some two and a half millennia, wears a different face than it did under the gaze of the Buddha himself. Witness, if you will, the island nation of Sri Lanka, where each year they perform the ritual of the water-cutting ceremony. Monks and those who dwell in the lay world come together in this rite, a thing of sacred import, though never taught by the Buddha in his time. Such shifts have crept from the surface to the very blood of the faith, altering its essence. The Theravada sect, through the years, has bent and reshaped its creed, driven by forces of many kinds, both from within and without, both with malice and without.

There are notions we must understand to speak of these changes. The force that rises from within, born of those who walk the Buddha's path, whether monk or householder, is internal. That which comes from those beyond the pale of the faith is external. Hostility is any breath of wind that seeks to harm, driven by disdain for the teachings. Benignity, on the other hand, is a force without intent to harm or aid, though its touch may do either.

We must first turn our gaze to the heart of this belief—the truths that beat within Theravada Buddhism. A refuge they seek, these followers, in the triple gem: the Buddha himself, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma lives in the Tripitaka, the three baskets that hold the words of the faith. The Sutta Pitaka keeps the teachings, the Vinaya Pitaka holds the rules of life, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka delves into the metaphysical. Here lie the bones of thought: Anatta, the absence of soul; Dukkha, the suffering that threads through life; Anicca, the fleeting nature of all things. One must grasp these truths to escape the wheel of Sansara, that endless cycle of death and rebirth. In this liberation, one casts off desire, hatred, and delusion, reaching for enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka lays down the law: the five precepts for the layman, simple yet binding—do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not stray in lust, and do not drink of substances that cloud the mind. For the monks, there are rules beyond count. And at the very core, the four noble truths: life is suffering; desire is its root; suffering can be vanquished.
